      <div class="SOTTO_PARA"><a name="DUC11c0e6002a5e10058d52d82abd9709d2"></a>Adjusting the rear shock absorber
      </div>
      <div class="SOTTO_PARA">
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3064"> </a>The shock absorber has external adjusters that enable you to adjust the set up to suit the load on the motorcycle.
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3066"> </a>The adjuster (1) on the shock absorber expansion reservoir controls compression damping.
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3068"> </a>Undo the screws (5) and remove the cover (4) to reach adjuster (1).
         </div>
      </div>
      <div class="AggancioFigure">
         <center><img class="Default" src="img/DUC_MO_MTS1200_4_015202872.jpg"></center>
      </div>
      <div class="AggancioFigure">
         <center><img class="Default" src="img/DUC_MO_MTS1200_4_015302873.jpg"></center>
      </div>
      <div class="SOTTO_PARA">
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3075"> </a>The adjuster&nbsp;(2), located on the left-hand side at the point at which the shock absorber is fixed to the swinging arm, controls
            rebound damping.
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3077"> </a>Turn the adjusters (1) and (2) clockwise to stiffen the damping or anticlockwise to soften it.
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3079"> </a>The adjuster knob (3), located on the left side of the motorcycle, adjusts the preload of the shock absorber external spring.
            Follow the instructions on the knob.
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3081"> </a>STANDARD setting corresponds to minimum position of adjuster knob (LOW).
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3083"> </a>STANDARD preloaded spring length on shock absorber: 162Â±1.5 mm.
         </div>
      </div>
      <div class="AggancioFigure">
         <center><img class="Default" src="img/DUC_MO_MTS1200_4_015402874.jpg"></center>
      </div>
      <div class="SOTTO_PARA">
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3088"> </a>STANDARD setting:
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3090"> </a>from fully closed (clockwise) loosen:
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3092"> </a>adjuster (1) by 1.5 clicks; 
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3094"> </a>adjuster (2) by 9 clicks.
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3096"> </a>Spring preload: 18 mm (Max. 18 mm - Min. 25 mm)
         </div>
      </div>
      <div class="Attenzione"><img class="Attenzione" width="28" height="25" style="display: inline; float: none; left: 0.0; text-align: left; top: 0.0;" src="img/warning.jpg">Warning
      </div>
      <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3099"> </a>The shock absorber is filled with high-pressure gas and can cause injuries if removed by unskilled personnel.
      </div>
      <div class="Attenzione"><img class="Attenzione" width="28" height="25" style="display: inline; float: none; left: 0.0; text-align: left; top: 0.0;" src="img/important.jpg">Important
      </div>
      <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e3102"> </a>If the motorcycle is to be ridden with a pillion rider and luggage, we recommend setting the rear shock absorber spring preload
         to the maximum to ensure the best handling and proper ground clearance at all times. It may also be necessary to adjust the
         rebound damping accordingly.
      </div>
